Forbes  , which ispronounced as two syllables in Aberdeenshire. Compare   Forbush  ."]},{"name":"Forbus","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Forbes  , reflecting thetraditional pronunciation as two syllables."]},{"name":"Forbush","meanings":["Scottish: altered form of   Forbes  , which was traditionally pronounced as two syllables. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Altered form of German <b>Vorbusch</b>, a topographic name for someone living on the edge of a wood, from <i>vor</i> ‘in front of’ + North German <i>Busch</i> ‘wood, bush’."]},{"name":"Fobbs","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  ."]},{"name":"Furbush","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Forbes  , which is traditionally pronounced as two syllables. Compare   Furbish  ."]},{"name":"Forbis","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  , reflecting the traditional pronunciation as two syllables."]},{"name":"Fobes","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  ."]},{"name":"Forbess","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  , reflecting the traditional pronunciation as two syllables."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander Forbes was born in 1256, in Forbes, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, his father, Fergus Forbes, was 30 and his mother, Mrs. Fergix de F